Lab 4: Mediation

Introduction to SEM with lavaan

Kyle M. Lang

Updated: 2022-07-04

In this lab, you will practice mediation analysis using lavaan and latent variables.

1 Data

We will first analyze the classic Holzinger & Swineford (1939) educational testing data. A full version of this dataset is distributed as the HS dataset in the MBESS package. We don’t need any functionality from MBESS, however, so I have provided a standalone (and mildly processed) version of the data as holzinger_swineford.rds.

These data contain a number of educational test scores from 7th and 8th grade students in two schools. These data contain 301 observations of the following 29 variables.

  • id: Numeric ID
  • age: Student age in years
  • sex: Biological sex of the student
  • grade: Grade of the student
  • school: School at which the student was tested
  • spatial1:spatial4: Scores on four spatial reasoning tests
  • verbal1:verbal5: Scores on five tests of verbal ability
  • speed1:speed4: Scores on four tests of cognitive processing speed
  • memory1:memory6: Scores on six memory tests
  • math1:math5: Scores on five tests of mathematical ability

In the following, we will use the test scores to define latent factors of the underlying ability levels.

You can access the original version of the data via the MBESS package, and you can access the code used to process the data here.

1.1

Read in the holzinger_swineford.rds dataset.

dataDir <- "../data/"
hs <- readRDS(paste0(dataDir, "holzinger_swineford.rds"))

NOTE: In the following, I will refer to these data as the HS data.

2 Simple Mediation 1

The first model we will consider is a simple mediation model wherein the effect of student age on spatial reasoning ability is mediated by mathematical ability.

  • We will include student age via the single item age
  • We will model spatial reasoning ability via a latent variable measured by the five spatial items.
  • We will model mathematical ability via a latent variable measured by the five math items.

2.1

Draw a path diagram for the model described above.

  • Label the relevant structural paths.

2.2

Write out the structural equations necessary to evaluate the mediation hypothesis described above.

\[ \begin{align} \eta_{spatial} &= b \eta_{math} + c' X_{age} + \varepsilon_2\\ \eta_{math} &= a X_{age} + \varepsilon_1 \end{align} \]

2.3

Define the model syntax for the CFA.

  • Indicated the spatial reasoning ability factor from the four observed spatial reasoning test scores.
    • spatial1:spatial4
  • Indicated the mathematical ability factor from the five observed math test scores.
    • math1:math5
cfaMod1 <- '
spatial =~ spatial1 + spatial2 + spatial3 + spatial4
math    =~ math1    + math2    + math3    + math4    + math5
'

2.4

Estimate the CFA model on the HS data.

  • Correlate the latent factors.
  • Set the scale by standardizing the latent factors.
  • Do not include any mean structure.
library(lavaan)
cfaFit1 <- cfa(cfaMod1, data = hs, std.lv = TRUE)

Summarize the fitted CFA and check the model fit.

  • Do the parameter estimates look sensible?

2.6

Define the model syntax for the structural model.

  • Specify all paths needed to test the mediation hypothesis described above.
  • Include a defined parameter to quantify the indirect effect.
## Define only the new structural parts:
semMod1 <- '
spatial ~ b * math + c * age
math    ~ a * age

ab := a * b
'

## Add on the measurement part:
semMod1 <- paste(cfaMod1, semMod1, sep = '\n')

2.7

Estimate the structural model.

  • Do not use bootstrapping.
  • Test the significance of the indirect effect using Sobel’s Z.
semFit1 <- sem(semMod1, data = hs, std.lv = TRUE)
summary(semFit1)

2.8

Interpret the results.

  1. Is the indirect effect significant according to the above test?
  2. Briefly interpret the indirect effect.
  3. What caveats might you place on this finding?

Answers:

  1. Yes, the indirect effect is statistically significant ( \(\hat{ab} = -0.261\), \(SE_{ab} = 0.094\), \(Z = -2.773\), \(p = 0.006\) ).
  2. There is a significant, negative effect of age on spatial reasoning ability transmitted through mathematical ability.
  3. The normality assumption underlying Sobel test may not be appropriate. We should test the significance of our indirect effect using bootstrapping.

2.9

Test the indirect effect using bootstrapping.

  • Rerun the structural model from 2.7 using \(B = 2000\) bootstrap resamples.
  • Test the significance of the indirect effect via the 95% BCa CI.
  • Is the indirect effect also significant according to the bootstrapped CI?
## Estimate the model with bootstrapped standard errors:
semFit1.2 <- sem(semMod1, 
                 data      = hs, 
                 std.lv    = TRUE, 
                 se        = "boot", 
                 bootstrap = 2000)

## Get the CI for the indirect effect:
parameterEstimates(semFit1.2, boot.ci.type = "bca.simple") %>% 
  select(-(1:3)) %>% 
  tail(1)

Yes, the 95% bootstrapped CI, (-0.488; -0.106), does not include zero, so we can infer a statistically significant indirect effect at the \(\alpha = 0.05\) level.

4 Parallel Multiple Mediation

Now, we will fit a multiple mediator model that combines the two simple mediation models evaluated above. This model will encode a process by which the effect of student age on spatial reasoning ability is indirectly transmitted by mathematical ability and verbal ability as parallel mediators.

4.1

Define the model syntax for the CFA.

  • Indicated the spatial reasoning ability factor from the four observed spatial reasoning test scores.
    • spatial1:spatial4
  • Indicated the mathematical ability factor from the five observed math test scores.
    • math1:math5
  • Indicated the verbal ability factor from the five observed verbal test scores.
    • verbal1:verbal5
cfaMod3 <- '
spatial =~ spatial1 + spatial2 + spatial3 + spatial4
math    =~ math1    + math2    + math3    + math4    + math5
verbal  =~ verbal1  + verbal2  + verbal3  + verbal4  + verbal5
'

Interpret the results.

  1. Is the specific indirect effect through mathematical ability significant according to the 95% BCa CI?
  2. Is the specific indirect effect through verbal ability significant according to the 95% BCa CI?
  3. Is the total indirect effect significant according to the 95% BCa CI?
  4. Briefly interpret the indirect effects.
  5. Do these results match the results from the separate simple mediation models?
    1. If you notice any differences, why do you think these differences occur?
parameterEstimates(semFit3, boot.ci.type = "bca.simple") %>% 
  select(-(1:3)) %>%
  tail(3)
  1. Yes, the specific indirect effect through mathematical ability is statistically significant ( \(\hat{ab} = -0.254\), \(95\%~CI_{BCa} = [-0.501; -0.094]\) ).
  2. No, the specific indirect effect through verbal ability is not statistically significant ( \(\hat{ab} = -0.011\), \(95\%~CI_{BCa} = [-0.09; 0.066]\) ).
  3. Yes, the total indirect effect is statistically significant ( \(\hat{IE} = -0.265\), \(95\%~CI_{BCa} = [-0.477; -0.097]\) ).
  4. There is a significant, negative indirect effect of age on spatial reasoning ability transmitted through mathematical ability, but verbal reasoning ability does not mediate a significant proportion of the effect of age on spatial reasoning ability, after controlling for mathematical ability. The total indirect effect of age on spatial reasoning ability transmitted through both mathematical ability and verbal ability is also statistically significant.
  5. Yes, verbal ability is a significant mediator in the simple mediation model, but it is not in the parallel mediation model.
    1. This difference probably arises from partialling out the effect of mathematical ability, which seems to be the more “important” mediator in this system.

5 Different Data

We will move on to a different dataset to explore serial mediator models. Specifically, we will work with a slightly modified version of the Eating Attitudes data used for some example analyses in Enders (2010). These data are available as eating_attitudes_completed.rds.

This dataset includes 400 observations of the following 14 variables. Note that the variables are listed in the order that they appear on the dataset.

  • id: A numeric ID

  • eat3:eat21: Three indicators of a Preoccupation with Food construct

  • anx: A single item assessing Anxiety Level

6 Serial Multiple Mediation

We will evaluate a serial multiple mediation model wherein the effect of Western Standards of Beauty on Preoccupation with Food is mediated by the sequential intermediaries Drive for Thinness and Anxiety. The causal process represented by our model would suggest that Western beauty standards induce a drive for thinness which, in turn, causes anxiety which, finally, leads to a preoccupation with food.

6.1

Draw a path diagram for the model described above.

  • Label the relevant structural paths.

6.2

Write out the structural equations necessary to evaluate the mediation hypothesis described above.

\[ \begin{align} \eta_{pre} &= b_1 \eta_{drive} + b_2 X_{anx} + c' X_{wsb} + \varepsilon_3\\ X_{anx} &= a_2 X_{wsb} + d \eta_{drive} + \varepsilon_2\\ \eta_{drive} &= a_1 X_{wsb} + \varepsilon_1 \end{align} \]

6.3

Define the model syntax for the CFA.

The data only contain multi-item scales for Drive for Thinness and Preoccupation with Food, so we only need a two-dimensional CFA evaluating the measurement structure of these two factors.

  • Indicated the Drive for Thinness factor from the seven relevant scale items.
    • eat1, eat2, eat10, eat11, eat12, eat14, eat24
  • Indicated the Preoccupation with Food factor from the remaining three scale items.
    • eat3, eat18, eat21
cfaMod4 <- '
drive =~ eat1 + eat2  + eat10 + eat11 + eat12 + eat14 + eat24
pre   =~ eat3 + eat18 + eat21
'

  • Correlate the latent factors.
  • Set the scale by standardizing the latent factors.
  • Do not include any mean structure.

6.8

Interpret the results.

  1. Is the two-step specific indirect effect through Drive for Thinness significant according to the 95% BCa CI?
  2. Is the two-step specific indirect effect through Anxiety significant according to the 95% BCa CI?
  3. Is the full, three-step specific indirect effect through Drive for Thinness and Anxiety significant according to the 95% BCa CI?
  4. Is the total indirect effect significant according to the 95% BCa CI?
  5. Briefly interpret the indirect effects.
parameterEstimates(semFit4, boot.ci.type = "bca.simple") %>% 
  select(-(1:3)) %>%
  tail(4)

  1. Yes, the two-step specific indirect effect through Drive for Thinness is statistically significant ( \(\hat{ab} = 0.122\), \(95\%~CI_{BCa} = [0.077; 0.173]\) ).

  2. No, the two-step specific indirect effect through anxiety is not statistically significant ( \(\hat{ab} = 0.002\), \(95\%~CI_{BCa} = [0; 0.026]\) ).

    • The lower bound of the CI rounds down to zero. Although one could conclude a just barely significant effect from the CI alone, the small point estimate and the large p-value for the bootstrapped z-test both suggest against inferring a significant effect.

  3. Yes, the full, three-step specific indirect effect is statistically significant ( \(\hat{adb} = 0.033\), \(95\%~CI_{BCa} = [0.018; 0.054]\) ).

  4. Yes, the total indirect effect is statistically significant ( \(\hat{IE} = 0.157\), \(95\%~CI_{BCa} = [0.104; 0.215]\) ).

  5. The hypothesized causal chain linking Western beauty standards to preoccupation with food through drive for thinness and anxiety was supported by a statistically significant specific indirect effect. Western beauty standards had a significant, positive effect on preoccupation with food, and this effect was transmitted indirectly by first increasing the drive for thinness which subsequently increased anxiety to, finally, increase preoccupation with food.

    A subprocess by which the effect of Western beauty standards on preoccupation with food is transmitted indirectly through drive for thinness was also supported by a statistically significant, positive indirect effect. The analogous subprocess transmitted through anxiety levels was associated with a nonsignificant indirect effect and, hence, not supported by these results.
